# Copy to ".env.local" (or export before build). Restart Vite after changes.
#
# Dev: if ICE/join still misbehaves after tinypeer patches, delete node_modules/.vite and restart
# npm run dev (clears Vite’s pre-bundled dependency cache). tinypeer is excluded from optimizeDeps.
#
# PeerJS signaling (tinypeer default: wss://0.peerjs.com). If WebSocket fails / "can't reach the server",
# deploy peerjs-server on a VPS and point the app here, then restart dev:
# VITE_PEERJS_HOST=your-peer.example.com
# VITE_PEERJS_PORT=443
# VITE_PEERJS_PATH=/peerjs
# VITE_PEERJS_KEY=peerjs
# VITE_PEERJS_SECURE=true
#
# Vite may print https://198.18.0.1:5173/ — that is NOT your LAN (often VPN/Clash fake-ip). Never open it on the phone;
# use only the https://192.168.x.x URL on both devices.
#
# Mac + iPhone ICE failures: try same Wi‑Fi on both, then optional:
# VITE_ICE_TRANSPORT_POLICY=relay
# (forces TURN-only; needs reachable TURN in VITE_ICE_SERVERS_JSON if public relay is blocked.)
#
# Full replacement for default ICE in src/peer.ts — JSON array of RTCIceServer.
# Use reachable STUN + TURN for your network (corporate Wi‑Fi often needs TURNS:443).
#
# Example (single line for .env):
# VITE_ICE_SERVERS_JSON=[{"urls":["stun:stun.l.google.com:19302"]},{"urls":"turn:YOUR_HOST:3478","username":"u","credential":"p"}]
